I am a power user on the Internet. I multi-task all the time and I need to be able to find what I am looking for quickly and easily without an hesitation. Google is my favorite search engine. I've tried them all. Google doesn't give you the awful advertising like Bing and it doesn't give you the scattered results like Yahoo. I have always been able to find what I want on Google without too much work on my part which is nice. I know a lot of people get frustrated with Google because they cannot find what they are looking for. I think part of that is people try to "change" what they want to find into words Google can understand. The thing is, Google doesn't work like other search engines, you can ask it a question like a human being, and it can find you an answer like a human being. You don't have to know computer lingo or any other codes to get the answer that you want from Google. For instance, if you want to know all of the movies that star a certain celebrity instead of typing "movies that star (celebrity name)" you can simply type "celebrity name movies" and get a list.One of my favorite parts about Google is how versatile the search is. If someone sends you a picture on the Internet that you think might be fake, you can click on images, drag and drop the photograph to Google, and find out if they just pulled the photograph right off the Internet. I love the image search because you can use it for just about everything. For instance, I found a black bug in my house with white spots, and I typed black bug with white spots into Google and then clicked images, and there are photographs of tons of bugs. All I do is click on the one that matches what I found, and I can instantly identify the bug. This is just one example of the way to use the image search. I also really like the news search feature on Google. If there is a specific news topic that you need to research you can type the topic in, click on news and it will give you a huge list of applicable news articles from sources all over the internet. They don't just pick and choose a few select "approved" news sources, but instead they give you every news source you can think of, even local news. The shopping search on Google is also very nice because it gives you a price comparison within Google without having to visit multiple websites. I love that I can see the price of an item at any store from E-bay to Walmart and every store in between. This allows me to shop for the best price every time I make a purchase without searching dozens of websites. I've compared prices on my own vs searching for prices under the Google shopping search and only once did I find a lower price on my own as opposed to the prices that Google showed. The books search is one of the most valuable. It will actually search parts of books and then highlight the phrase you searched for in that book. It's invaluable for research when you need to quote your sources. I don't know how I ever got through college without it (because it didn't exist back then). The maps are also something that I love, from locating a new restaurant to getting driving directions to the doctor's office, I love that I can type in any location in the world, click on maps, and get a map of the location and/or driving directions to and from the location. It incorporates Google Earth type technology, but loads faster and easier, and it's available on the Internet vs downloading Google Earth to your computer. Google is close to perfect, which is saying a lot for a search engine. The one thing I would change is the fact that it stores pages that no longer exist. I've found ways around this, by submitting removal requests for information, but at the end of the day, I wish Google could check for web pages that no longer exist so that I did not have to click on multiple websites only to find out that the information is no longer thereI will continue to use Google as long as it's superior to other search engines, and I don't see that changing any time soon!

It has been over 30 days since I signed-up for the Google product Adsense and my account has neither been approved or denied. There is not anything in the help or support sections that I can use until Google tells me what is going on.Google makes it impossible to contact them directly and actively uses its technology to avoid interaction. I do not want you to just believe me. I want you to test the Google help and support features before you sign up for a Google program and see for yourself. Ask yourself- is this a level of support that is satisfactory for me? Google would rather customers rely on user forums for problem solving. Even if I give Google the benefit of the doubt and they just want customers to help each other to build some sort of peer team spirit, there are some very good reasons user forums are questionable for customer service.1. There is not any obligation on the part of other users to answer a question so many questions go unanswered.2. Many well meaning members of a user forum are not familiar enough with Google products or providing customer service and will give incomplete or overly technical answers that are useless to the help seeker.3. Google is weakening itself. Google.s competition could easily be monitoring Google's user forums for technical information and weaknesses in Google products that can be used to build something better. Making customers rely on each other makes it easy for them to give away valuable product details publicly. Frustrated customers are going to feel obligated to post the technical details of  the Google products they use all over the internet seeking help with their problem if Google does not provide direct product troubleshooting service of its own products. Thus, by providing poor customer service Google is pushing customers to give away its secrets.I was lucky, I found out about Google’s lack of customer service before I signed-up for a Google application that required a payment. What Google seems to be forgetting is that first impressions count for so much in business and there are now many others out there like me who may never trust Google with a paid product because of Google's attitude toward customer service.The other thing Google forgets is that my success using their application also allows Google to earn additional revenue.Hold on. Wow. Suddenly I am not so upset. Google's lack of customer service is costing them money as well. When I multiply it out for everyone Google is probably frustrating with its customer service policies, Google must be developing a serious revenue leak somewhere.Hey Google-let me remind you that there was another seemingly unstoppable internet powerhouse that failed because of poor customer relations as much as any other reason: AOL. Think about it.
